definition.value: An organic heteropentacyclic compound that is 2,3,3a,12a-tetrahydroanthra[2,3-b]furo[3,2-d]furan-5,10-dione carrying three hydroxy substituents at positions 4, 6 and 8.
A phytocassane that is (+)-phytocassane C in which the hydroxy group at position 3 has been oxidised to the give corresponding ketone.
An organic heteropentacyclic compound that is 3a,12a-dihydroanthra[2,3-b]furo[3,2-d]furan-5,10-dione carrying three hydroxy substituents at positions 4, 6 and 8.
A sterigmatocystin whose skeleton comprises a xanthone ring system ortho-fused to a dihydrofuranofuran moiety.
A sterigmatocystin that is the 8-O-methyl derivative of dihydrosterigmatocystin.
A sterigmatocystin that is the 11-hydroxy-8-O-methyl derivative of dihydrosterigmatocystin.
A sterigmatocystin that is the 11-hydroxy-8-O-methyl derivative of the parent sterigmatocystin.
An optically active form of versiconol acetate having 3S-configuration.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 1-lauroyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate.
An anionic phospholipid obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 1-myristoyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate.
A ketoaldonic acid phosphate consisting of 3-deoxy-D-manno-oct-2-ulosonic acid having a phospho group at the 4-position.
A non-ribosomally synthesised dipeptide that consists of L-alanyl and anticapsin units linked by a peptide bond.
An alkane that has 36 carbons and a straight-chain structure.
An O-acylcarnitine having oleoyl as the acyl substituent.

An aromatic amine that is thalidomide substituted at position 4 on the isoindole ring system by an amino group. Used for the treatment of multiple myeloma in patients who failed to respond to previous therapies.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid that is deca-2,8-dien-4-ynoic acid substituted at position 10 by a hydroxy group (the 2E,8E-geoisomer)
Any fatty aldehyde containing more than one double or triple bond located at any position in the aliphatic chain.
Any C18 polyunsaturated fatty aldehyde containing two double bonds.
A chiral tricarboxylic acid in which a central carbon carries hydroxy, carboxy, carboxymethyl and 3-carboxypropyl substituents with R-configuration at the chiral centre.
Any molecule that consists of at least one carbon atom as part of the electrically neutral entity.
An anthocyanin cation found in the leaves and stems of Arabidopsis thaliana.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups of (R)-dihomocitric acid; major structure at pH 7.3.
A chiral tricarboxylic acid in which a central carbon carries hydroxy, carboxy, carboxymethyl and 4-carboxybutyl substituents with R-configuration at the chiral centre.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups of (2R)-trihomocitric acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An oxo dicarboxylic acid that is pimelic acid carrying a single oxo substituent at position 2.
An oxo dicarboxylate obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of 2-oxopimelic acid; major structure at pH 7.3.
An organic chloride salt in which the cationic component is 1,3-dimethyl-2-[(2-oxopropyl)thio]imidazolium.
A tetrapeptide comprising N-(tert-butoxycarbonyl)-6-diazo-5-oxo-L-norleucyl, L-glutaminyl, L-isoleucyl and methyl L-valinate residues coupled in sequence.
Any organic cation that consists of a chromenylium skeleton and its substituted derivatives thereof.
An anthocyanin cation found in the leaves and stems of Arabidopsis thaliana.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of both nitrogen atoms of bedaquiline.
An optically active form of tricyclic versicolorone having S-configuration.
A tricarboxylic acid that consists of pent-1-ene having three carboxy groups located at positions 1, 2 and 5 (the Z-geoisomer).
Any lignan condensed with a 2-aryl-1-benzopyran skeleton and its substituted derivatives.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups of cis-dihomoaconitic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A tricarboxylic acid that consists of hex-1-ene having three carboxy groups located at positions 1, 2 and 6 (the Z-geoisomer).
A tricarboxylic acid trianion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups of cis-trihomoaconitic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A tricarboxylic acid that is pimelic acid carrying an additional carboxy substituent at position 3 as well as a hydroxy substituent at position 2 (the 2R,3S-diastereomer).
Any C24 straight-chain fatty acid containing six C=C double bonds.
An O-octadecadienoylcarnitine having linoelaidyl as the acyl substituent.
An EC 2.3.2.* (aminoacyltransferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of protein-glutamine gamma-glutamyltransferase (EC 2.3.2.13).
An imidazolium ion obtained by methylation at position 3 of 1-methyl-2-[(2-oxopropyl)thio]imidazole.
A ceramide 1-phosphate that is the N-dodecanoyl (lauroyl) derivative of sphingosine.
A linear tetrapyrrole, product of heme degradation. An isomer of bilirubin.
A phenylpropanoid obtained by the coupling of two or more units of aryl-substituted benzopyran units and their substituted derivatives.

A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are eicosatetraenoyl (C20 straight-chain containing four C=C double bonds) and octadecenoyl (C18 straight-chain containing one C=C double bond) group respectively.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups of (-)-threo-isodihomocitric acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide formed from two L-phenylalanine residues.
